						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Underground-solution-to-starving-rice-plants" title="Underground solution to starving rice plants" alt="link">Underground solution to starving rice plants</a></h2>

	
					<p>A rice gene that could significantly raise the rate of phosphorus uptake in rice varieties has been discovered by a team of international researchers, who claim that it could increase rice yields by up to 20%. The gene is called PSTOL1, which stands for Phosphorus Starvation Tolerance. It enhances the root growth of rice plants, enabling them to acquire more phosphorous and other nutrients locked in soils. Sigrid Heuer, a senior scientist at the International Rice Research Institute (IRRI) in the Philippines, and leader of the team that published the study in Nature (August 2012), said low phosphorus availability in soils affects about half of the world's farmlands. Affected soils require additional applications of phosphorous fertiliser to make them productive.(Excerpt from <a href="http://www.scidev.net/en/agriculture-and-environment/news/phosphorus-uptake-gene-could-boost-rice-yields-.html" target="_blank">Scidev</a>, 30/8/2012, <a href="http://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2012/08/120823113124.htm" target="_blank">Sciencedaily</a>, <a href="http://www.isaaa.org/kc/cropbiotechupdate/article/default.asp?ID=10048" target="_blank">ISAAA</a>).</p>
							<p><span class="date">19/10/2012</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/Dossiers/CTA-and-S-T/Developments/Underground-solution-to-starving-rice-plants">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
